<Layout 
  title="International Treaties | Policy"
  description="Understand how international treaties and agreements affect the UK Armed Forces Compensation Scheme. Learn about reciprocal arrangements and implications for service abroad.">
  <div class="container my-5">
    <h1 class="display-4 mb-4">International Treaties and AFCS</h1>
    <div class="row g-4">
      <div class="col-lg-8">
        <p class="lead">The Armed Forces Compensation Scheme (AFCS) is influenced by various international treaties and agreements. This page outlines key international arrangements and their implications for service personnel and veterans.</p>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">NATO Status of Forces Agreement (SOFA)</h2>
        <p>The NATO SOFA affects AFCS claims in several ways:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Establishes rules for compensation when serving in NATO countries</li>
          <li>Defines jurisdictional issues for injuries occurring abroad</li>
          <li>Outlines procedures for claims involving multiple nations' forces</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Bilateral Agreements</h2>
        <p>The UK has bilateral agreements with several countries, which can affect compensation claims:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Reciprocal healthcare arrangements</li>
          <li>Agreements on liability and compensation for injuries</li>
          <li>Provisions for joint military exercises and operations</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">UN Peacekeeping Missions</h2>
        <p>For personnel involved in UN peacekeeping:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>UN compensation schemes may apply in certain circumstances</li>
          <li>Interaction between UN benefits and AFCS entitlements</li>
          <li>Special considerations for injuries sustained during UN missions</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">European Union Agreements</h2>
        <p>Despite Brexit, some EU agreements still affect AFCS:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Transitional arrangements for pre-Brexit claims</li>
          <li>Ongoing negotiations for future cooperation</li>
          <li>Implications for service personnel stationed in EU countries</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Geneva Conventions</h2>
        <p>The Geneva Conventions influence aspects of AFCS, particularly:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Treatment of injuries sustained in conflict</li>
          <li>Obligations towards prisoners of war</li>
          <li>Compensation for violations of international humanitarian law</li>
        </ul>
        
        <h2 class="h3 mt-4">Implications for Claimants</h2>
        <p>International treaties can affect AFCS claims in several ways:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Determining which country's compensation scheme applies</li>
          <li>Potential for additional or alternative compensation sources</li>
          <li>Complexities in claims involving multiple jurisdictions</li>
          <li>Timelines and procedures for international claims</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="card bg-light mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h3 class="h5">Related Information</h3>
            <ul class="list-unstyled">
              <li><a href="/policy/legislation" class="text-decoration-none">AFCS Legislation</a></li>
              <li><a href="/eligibility/service-requirements" class="text-decoration-none">Service Requirements</a></li>
              <li><a href="/support/legal-assistance" class="text-decoration-none">Legal Assistance</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card mb-4">
          <div class="card-body">
            <h3 class="h5">International Claims Advice</h3>
            <p>For guidance on claims involving international service, contact our specialist advisors.</p>
            <a href="/international-claims" class="btn btn-primary">Get Advice</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
